SARIMAX Explained Simply

SARIMAX stands for:

S → Seasonal
A → AutoRegressive
R → Integrated
I → Moving Average
M → eXogenous Variables

SARIMA vs SARIMAX
SARIMA

Uses only past values of the target variable.

Example:

Yesterday Bookings
↓
Today Forecast

Question:

Can we predict future hotel bookings using only past hotel bookings?

Answer:
Yes, using SARIMA.

SARIMAX

Uses past values plus external factors.

Example:

Past Hotel Bookings
+
Room Price (ADR)
+
Lead Time
+
Special Requests
↓
Future Booking Forecast

This is SARIMAX.

Real-Time Example

Imagine a hotel.

Target Variable (Y):

Daily Bookings

External Variables (X):

Room Price
Weekend/Holiday
Lead Time
Number of Guests
Special Requests

These factors affect booking demand.

SARIMAX learns:

Higher Room Price
↓
Lower Bookings

Festival Season
↓
Higher Bookings

More Lead Time
↓
Higher Future Bookings
Formula

SARIMAX is:

Forecast
=
SARIMA Components
+
External Variables (X)

or

Y = SARIMA + X

where:

Y = Target Variable
X = External Variables
